Relationship between Weight and MPG (Miles Per Gallon):

  • As weight increases, MPG tends to decrease, indicating that heavier vehicles generally have lower fuel efficiency.
  • This negative correlation suggests that weight is a significant factor influencing the fuel economy of vehicles.

Impact of Cylinder Size on Weight and MPG:

  • Additionally, the scatterplot illustrates a trend where cylinder size, represented by the 'cyl' variable, tends to increase with weight.
  • Vehicles with a greater number of cylinders exhibit higher weight, which aligns with the expectation that larger engines contribute to increased vehicle weight.
  • However, despite the increase in weight with cylinder size, MPG tends to decrease.
  • This observation underscores the trade-off between engine power (often associated with larger cylinders) and fuel efficiency, where vehicles with larger engines may sacrifice MPG for performance.

The insights fetched from the scatterplot emphasize the interplay between weight, cylinder size, and MPG in determining the fuel efficiency and performance characteristics of vehicles. While heavier vehicles and larger engine sizes may offer enhanced power and performance, they typically come at the expense of reduced fuel efficiency, as indicated by the negative correlation between weight and MPG. This trade-off underscores the importance of optimizing vehicle design and engine specifications to strike a balance between performance and fuel economy, addressing the diverse needs and preferences of consumers.

# Function to find special characters in a string
def find_special_characters(text):
    special_characters = re.compile(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]')
    return special_characters.findall(text)

# Function to check if a string consists of only numeric characters
def is_numeric1(text):
    print(text.replace('.', '', 1).isdigit())
    return text.replace('.', '', 1).isdigit()
#Lets check if each column has any special characters and blank values
for column in dfMerged.columns:
    if column != 'car_name':
        for index, value in dfMerged[column].items():
            if isinstance(value, str) and value.strip():  # Check if the value is a non-empty string                
                special_chars = find_special_characters(value)
                if special_chars:
                    print(f"Special characters found in column '{column}', row '{index}': {special_chars}")                
            elif isinstance(value, float) and np.isnan(value):  # Check if the value is NaN
                print(f"Blank value found in column '{column}', row '{index}'")

Q.2. Clustering:

Q.2.A. Apply K-Means clustering for 2 to 10 clusters.

In[16]:
#lets drop column car name before applying clustering
df = dfMerged.drop('car_name',axis = 1)

#lets scale the data as features are having different unit of measures
# scaled_df = df.apply(zscore)
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_data  = scaler.fit_transform(df)
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data, columns=df.columns)

#Lets apply kmeans clustering for k=2-10
clusters=range(2,11)
meanDistortions=[]
wss = []
for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(scaled_df)
    # prediction=model.predict(scaled_df)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / scaled_df.shape[0])
    #Lets store in cluster sum of squares
    wss.append(model.inertia_)

Q.3.B. Plot a visual and find elbow point.

In[17]:
#Lets plot average distortion and within cluster sum of squares against different k values in separate plots
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  # Subplot 1: Average Distortion
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method (Average Distortion)')

# Plotting WSS
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)  # Subplot 2: WSS
plt.plot(range(2, 11), wss, 'ro-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WSS)')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method (WSS)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Q.3.C. On the above visual, highlight which are the possible Elbow points.

Form above plot of avg distortion against k values, it can be infered that there are two points which can be considered as elbow points.

  1. k = 5 There is considerable deviation at this point
  2. k = 7 This also signifies deviation so this also can be considered as elbow point

Both of these points can be considered as elbow points and can be used to find optimum k to find best clustering.

final_model=KMeans(n_clusters = 5, random_state=0)

labels = final_model.labels_

Q.2. Data Preparation:

Note: Steps/data approach to be followed :

  1. Split data to X and y
  2. Split data to X_Train, y_train (Training) X_test, y_test (Testing data)
  3. We will scale data training, testing for initial SVM and original X data for PCA
  4. We will perform SVM on training data and will test the model on test data
  5. We will perform PCA on whole scaled data (X_scaled)
  6. Post PCA dimensionality reduction, we will split this data into train and test to again perform SVM
  7. Further, we will use same (PCA) data for SVM with tuned parameters
  8. Performance improvement / reduction measuring after PCA/dimensionality reduction.

In[35]:
#Lets define a function to store result of each model/combination in dataframe results_df
columns = ['Model','train_acc','test_acc','train_recall','test_recall','train_precision','test_precision','Train_F1','Test_F1']
results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)
def AddModelResults(df, Model,train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision,Train_F1,Test_F1):
    if (df['Model'] == Model).any(): 
        df.loc[df['Model'] == Model, ['Model','train_acc','test_acc','train_recall','test_recall','train_precision','test_precision','Train_F1','Test_F1']] = [Model, train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision,Train_F1,Test_F1]
    else:
        # Append a new row        
        new_row = {'Model': Model,'train_acc' : train_acc,'test_acc':test_acc,'train_recall':train_recall,'test_recall':test_recall,'train_precision':train_precision,'test_precision':test_precision, 'Train_F1' : Train_F1,'Test_F1' : Test_F1 }
        df = pd.concat([df, pd.DataFrame([new_row])], ignore_index=True)
    return df

# function that actually used to train model and print/save th eoutput of the model
def PrintOutput(dfr,name,Xtrain, Xtest, ytrain, ytest,pred_train, pred_test ): 
    # pred_train = np.round(pred_train,2)
    # pred_test = np.round(pred_test,2)
    
    train_acc = np.round(accuracy_score(y_train,pred_train),2)
    test_acc = np.round(accuracy_score(ytest,pred_test),2)
    
    train_recall = np.round(recall_score(ytrain,pred_train, average='weighted'),2)
    test_recall = np.round(recall_score(ytest,pred_test, average='weighted'),2)
    
    train_precision = np.round(precision_score(ytrain,pred_train, average='weighted'),2)
    test_precision = np.round(precision_score(ytest,pred_test, average='weighted'),2)
    train_f1 = np.round(f1_score(ytrain,pred_train, average='weighted'),2)
    test_f1 = np.round(f1_score(ytest, pred_test, average='weighted'),2)
    classification_rep = classification_report(ytest, pred_test)    
    
    print('*'*15, name, '*'*15)
    print("Accuracy on training set : ",train_acc)
    print("Accuracy on test set : ",test_acc)
    print("Recall on training set: ",train_recall)
    print("Recall on test set: ",test_recall)
    print("Precision on training set: ",train_precision)
    print("Precision on test set: ",test_precision)
    print("F1 on train set: ",train_f1)
    print("F1 on test set: ",test_f1)  
    print("Classification Report on test data:")
    print(classification_rep)
    return train_acc, train_recall, train_precision, train_f1,test_acc, test_recall, test_precision, test_f1, AddModelResults(dfr, name,train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision,train_f1,test_f1)

The comparison above reveals several key insights:

Q.5. Data Understanding & Cleaning

Q.5.A. Explain pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA.

  • Linearity: The relationships between the variables in the data should be linear. If the relationships are non-linear, PCA may not be able to effectively capture the underlying structure of the data.

  • Multivariate normality: The variables in the data should be multivariate normally distributed. If the data is not normally distributed, PCA may not be able to accurately represent the relationships between the variables.

  • Absence of multicollinearity: The variables in the data should not be highly correlated. If multicollinearity is present, PCA may not be able to identify the most important principal components.

  • Homogeneity of variance: The variances of the variables in the data should be approximately equal. If the variances are not equal, PCA may be biased towards the variables with larger variances.

Q.5.B. Explain advantages and limitations of PCA.

Advantages:

  • Dimensionality reduction: PCA can be used to reduce the dimensionality of a dataset by identifying the most important features. This can make it easier to visualize and interpret the data, and can also improve the performance of machine learning models.

In above example, we reduced features from 19 to 6 without loss of any much of the information

  • Removes multi-collinearity to improve ML model performance We noticed that data with 19 columns were highly correlated among features. However, PCA removed multicolinearity after dimensionality reduction.
  • Decreases computational times for fitting models. We saw SVM with parameter tuning was quite fast on PCA data
  • Makes visualization easy

Decreases storage requirements Avoids curse of dimensionait y Helps reduce over fitting

  • Noise reduction: PCA can be used to remove noise from a dataset by identifying and removing the principal components that are associated with noise. This can improve the quality of the data and make it more useful for machine learning models.
  • Feature extraction: PCA can be used to extract new features from a dataset. These features can be used to improve the performance of machine learning models or to gain a better understanding of the data.

Limitations:

  • Assumes linearity: PCA assumes that the relationships between the variables in the dataset are linear. If the relationships are non-linear, PCA may not be able to effectively capture the underlying structure of the data.
  • Sensitive to outliers: PCA is sensitive to outliers in the dataset. Outliers can distort the principal components and make it difficult to interpret the results.
  • Can be computationally expensive: PCA can be computationally expensive, especially for large datasets.

Overall, PCA is a powerful tool that can be used to reduce dimensionality, remove noise, and extract new features from a dataset. However, it is important to be aware of the assumptions and limitations of PCA before using it.
